</paragraphs>

<paragraphs>
<title>Refining the Definition</title>

<p>
<xref ref="DEFINITIONsecond-inad-limit-at-infinity">Definition</xref> works as long as
<m>f(x)\gt 0</m>, but without this restriction it fails utterly as our
next example shows:
</p>

<example xml:id="EXAMPLElimit1">
<p>
  Suppose <m>f(x) = -2-\frac{1}{x}.</m> Can you guess the value of <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}</m>?

  Let <m>\eps\gt 0</m> be given. Then when <m>B</m> has any positive
  value,  if <m>x\gt B</m> we have
  <me>
  f(x) = -2-\frac1x \lt  0 \lt  \eps,
  </me>
  and by <xref ref="DEFINITIONsecond-inad-limit-at-infinity"></xref> we
  conclude that <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{f(x)} =0</m> since all of the requirements
  of our definition have been met (except, of course, <m>f(x)\gt0</m>).

  Of course, this is nonsense. As we have noted  as <m>x</m> increases without bound
  <m>\frac1x</m> gets arbitrarily close to zero. So clearly
  <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=-2</m>. That we are able to <q>prove</q> that
  <m>f(x)</m> goes to zero simply means that
  <xref ref="DEFINITIONsecond-inad-limit-at-infinity"></xref> doesn<rsq/>t capture
  everything we need.

  We need a more encompassing definition of a limit.
  </p>
</example>
<p>

Based on our experience in <xref ref="EXAMPLElimit1">Example</xref> with
<m>f(x) = -2-\frac1x</m>, what would you say needs to be changed in
<xref ref="DEFINITIONsecond-inad-limit-at-infinity"></xref> to allow
<m>f(x)\le0</m> as well?
</p>
<p>


The problem of course, is that if <m>\eps\gt 0</m> is given the statement <m>f(x) \lt  \eps</m> doesn<rsq/>t
really capture the idea that <m>f(x)</m> is near the number zero, only that it
is less than the number <m>\eps</m>. For example,  <m>-1000</m> is less than
<m>\eps</m> but it is nowhere near zero. What we need is a way to measure
how far <m>f(x)</m> is from zero, regardless of whether in the positive or
the negative direction.
</p>
<p>

 That is exactly what the absolute value function
measures. For example, both <m>3</m> and <m>-3</m> are the same distance from
zero, the first  one in the positive and the second one in the
negative direction. That is
<m>\abs{3}=\abs{-3}=3</m>.
</p>
<p>


We need to modify our definition so that the distance from <m>y</m> to zero
is less than <m>\eps</m>. We want <m>\abs{y}\lt \eps,</m> not just
<m>y\lt \eps</m>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="DEFINITIONlimit-at-infinity-nearly-adequate">
<title>Zero Limit at Infinity</title>
<statement>
<p>
  <!-- \label{def:limit-at-infinity-nearly-adequate} -->
  Suppose <m>f(x)</m> is defined for all <m>x\gt 0</m>. Then we say that
  <m>
  \limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=0
  </m>
  if and only if for every <m>\eps\gt 0</m> we can find a real number <m>B</m> with
  the property that whenever <m>x\gt B,</m> <m>\abs{f(x)}\lt \eps.</m>

</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="EXAMPLEFormalLimitProof1">
<title>First:</title>
<p>
  Suppose <m>f(x) = -\frac1{x}</m>. We want to prove  rigorously
that <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=0</m>.
</p>
</example>
<investigation>
<p>

 Let <m>\eps\gt0</m> be given.
</p>

<p>
 As we did in <xref ref="EXAMPLELimPosFuncInf"></xref> we find the bound <m>B</m> by working the problem backwards. We want to
  end with <m>\abs{f(x)}\lt\eps</m>, so that<rsq/>s where we start.
</p>
<p>
Since we are only interested in what happens to <m>f(x)</m>
    as <m>x\rightarrow\infty</m>, we can safely assume that
    <m>x\gt0</m>. In that case if
<me>\abs{f(x)} \lt\eps</me>
then it follows that
<me>\abs{-1/x}=1/x \lt\eps,</me>

<!-- <md> -->
<!-- <mrow>\abs{f(x)}\amp \lt\eps</mrow> -->
<!-- <mrow>\abs{-1/x}=1/x\amp \lt\eps.</mrow> -->
<!-- </md> -->
and if
<m>\frac1x \lt\eps</m> then
<m>x \gt 1/\eps</m>,
<!-- <me>\abs{\frac{-1}{x}}=\frac{1}{x},</me> -->
<!-- so -->

<!-- <md> -->
<!-- <mrow>\frac1x\amp \lt\eps</mrow> -->
<!-- <mrow>x\amp \gt\frac1\eps.</mrow> -->
<!-- </md> -->
so apparently to make <m> \abs{f(x)}\lt\eps</m> we need
<m>x\gt\frac1\eps</m>. So we take <m>B=\frac1\eps</m>.
</p>
<p>
<alert>END OF SCRAPWORK</alert>
</p>
</investigation>

<!-- <aside> -->
<!-- <title>Note to self</title> -->
<!-- <p> -->
<!-- Absolute value is not showing up in this proof. -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- </aside> -->


<proof>
<p>
  Let <m>\eps\gt0</m> be given. Take <m>B\gt\frac1\eps</m>.

  If <m>x\gt B</m> then

  
<me>x \gt\frac{1}{\eps}.</me>
Therefore
<me>    \frac{1}{x} \lt \eps</me>
and
<me>    \abs{\frac{-1}{x}} \lt \eps.</me>
So
<me>    \abs{f(x)} \lt \eps.</me>


  Therefore, by
  <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-infinity-nearly-adequate"></xref>
  <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=0</m>.
</p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>

<p>
This example displays the format of a limit proof that you need to
adhere to. Below is an outline of the format. This is not a course in
creative writing. Do not depart from this format.
<dl>
<li>
<title>First:</title>
<p>
 State the challenge, <m>\eps\gt0</m>.
</p>
</li>
<li>
<title>Second:</title>
<p>
 Specify the bound  <m>B</m> (usually in terms of <m>\eps</m>).
</p>
</li>
<li>
<title>Third:</title>
<p>
 Show that if <m>x\gt B</m> then <m>\abs{f(x)}\lt\eps</m>.
</p>
</li>
<li>
<title>Fourth:</title>
<p>
State your conclusion.
</p>
</li>
</dl>

</p>

<exercise>
<statement>
<p>
  Identify which statements in the proof in <xref
  ref="EXAMPLEFormalLimitProof1"></xref> correspond to the first,
  second, third, and fourth parts of the format presented above.
</p>
</statement>
</exercise>



<example xml:id="EXAMPLEFormalLimitProof2">
<p>
  Our previous examples and problems in this section were fairly
  simple as formal limit problems go. This one is more complex.
</p>
<p>
  
  Use  <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-infinity-nearly-adequate"></xref> to show that
  <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{\frac{1}{5x-x^2}}=0</m>.
</p>
</example>

  <investigation>
<p>
   For a given <m>\eps\gt0</m>, we want to end up with
    <me>
    \abs{\frac{1}{5x-x^2}}\lt\eps.
    </me>
    Part of what makes this limit more complex is that the part inside
    the absolute value <m>\frac{1}{5x-x^2}</m>, is not always positive.  We
    need to deal with that somehow.
</p>
<p>

 First, since we are only concerned about what happens as
 <m>x\rightarrow\infty</m> it  is safe to assume that <m>x\gt0</m>. In that
 case, <m>x=\abs{x}</m>.
    Next, observe that if  <m>x\gt 5</m> also, then <m>x^2\gt 5x</m>. Thus <m>5x-x^2\lt0</m>, so
    that <m>\abs{\frac{1}{5x-x^2}}=\frac{1}{x^2-5x}</m>. We could now work
    backwards like before, and solve for
    <m>\frac{1}{x^2-5x}\lt\eps</m>. This will work fine, but the Algebra
    gets very messy. Try it and see.
</p>
<p>

    There is a sneaky way to do this that avoids some of the Algebra.
    Notice that <m>\frac{1}{x^2-5x}=\left(\frac{1}{x-5}\right)\cdot\left(\frac1x\right)</m>. Notice
    further that if <m>x\gt6</m>, then <m>x-5\gt1</m> so that
    <m>\frac{1}{x-5}\lt1</m>.  Putting all of this together we we that for
    <m>x\gt6</m>,

    <md>
      <mrow>      \abs{\frac{1}{5x-x^2}}\amp =\abs{\frac{1}{5-x}}\cdot\abs{\frac1x}</mrow>
      <mrow>      \amp =\left(\frac{1}{x-5}\right)\cdot\left(\frac1x\right)</mrow>
      <mrow>      \amp \lt 1\cdot\left(\frac1x\right)=\frac1x.</mrow>
    </md>

</p>
<p>

    Thus to guarantee that <m> \abs{\frac{1}{5x-x^2}}\lt\eps</m> we need
    <m>\frac1x\lt\eps</m>, or <m>x\gt\frac{1}{\eps}</m>.
</p>
<p>
<alert>END OF SCRAPWORK</alert>
</p>
  </investigation>
  <proof>
<p>
    Let <m>\eps\gt0</m> be given. Let <m>B</m> be the larger of <m>6</m> and
    <m>\frac1\eps</m>. If <m>x\gt B</m> then <m>x\gt6</m> so <m>x-5\gt1</m>. Therefore
    <men  xml:id="EQUATIONProofPractice1">
      <!-- \label{eq:ProofPractice1} -->
      \abs{\frac{1}{5-x}}=\frac{1}{x-5}\lt1.
  </men>
    Since <m>x\gt\frac1\eps\gt0</m>, we see that  <m>\abs{\frac{1}{x}}=\frac{1}{\abs{x}}=\frac1x\lt\eps</m>.  Thus
    <men  xml:id="EQUATIONProofPractice2">
      <!-- \label{eq:ProofPractice2} -->
      \abs{\frac{1}{5x-x^2}}=\abs{\frac{1}{5-x}}\cdot\abs{\frac1x}\lt1\cdot\frac1x\lt\eps.
  </men>
    Therefore by
    <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-infinity-nearly-adequate"></xref>,
    <me>
    \limit{x}{\infty}{\frac{1}{5x-x^2}}=0.
    </me>
  </p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>


<problem xml:id="PROBLEMProofPractice1">
<statement>
<p>
  Explain carefully, and in detail, the reasoning that supports the
  claims made in Equations <xref ref="EQUATIONProofPractice1"></xref> and
  <xref ref="EQUATIONProofPractice2"></xref>.
</p>
</statement>
</problem>
<p>

Notice that in <xref ref="EXAMPLEFormalLimitProof1"></xref> and <xref
ref="EXAMPLEFormalLimitProof2"></xref> that the scrapwork was an
essential part of the solution, but in the formal proof the results of
the scrapwork were so abbreviated as to almost not be present. This is
part of the formalism of mathematical writing. We try to make sure
that everything that needs to be said is said <mdash/> and absolutely
nothing more.  In this instance in particular, we are not obligated to
explain where the bound <m>B</m> came from, only that it works. It can
take time to become comfortable with this presentation style.
</p>
<p>

Even with practice very few people can read a formal proof without
doing the computations necessary to show that all of the claims made
are actually true. Keep paper and pencil handy at all times to help
you follow the argument.
</p>

