<p>
<xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-infinity-nearly-adequate">Definition</xref> only tells us
what it means
when the limit of some function as <m>x\rightarrow\infty</m> is zero.  But as we observed in
<xref ref="EXAMPLElimit1">Example</xref> as <m>x</m> increases without bound
<m>f(x)=-2-\frac1x</m> approaches <m>-2</m>, not <m>0</m>.  We<rsq/>ll need something more
general, but all of the important ideas have been introduced. We
generalize <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-infinity-nearly-adequate"></xref> as
follows.
</p>

<definition xml:id="DEFINITIONlimit-at-posinfinity">
<title>A Limit at <m>+\infty</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
  <!-- \label{def:limit-at-posinfinity} -->
  Suppose that <m>L</m> is a real number and that <m>f(x)</m> is defined for all
  <m>x\gt 0</m>. Then we say that
  <me>
  \limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=L
  </me>
  if and only if for every <m>\eps\gt 0</m> there is a real number <m>B</m>
  with the property that whenever <m>x\gt B,</m>
  <m>\abs{f(x)-L}\lt \eps.</m>
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
Notice that if <m>L=0</m> this
    reduces to  <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-infinity-nearly-adequate"></xref>.
</p>


<example>
<p>
  Suppose <m>f(x)=1-\frac1x</m>. Intuitively, it is clear that
  <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=1</m> but we need to prove that this is so.
</p>
</example>

  <investigation>
<p>
    Suppose <m>\eps\gt0</m> is given.  We need to specify a number <m>B</m>
    (probably in terms of <m>\eps</m>), with
    the property that if <m>x\gt B</m> then <m>
    \abs{f(x) - 1}\lt \eps.
    </m>
    So we will work backwards from   this inequality.
    <md>
      <mrow>
        \abs{f(x) - 1}\amp \lt \eps
      </mrow>
      <mrow>\abs{\left(1-\tfrac1x\right) - 1}\amp \lt \eps</mrow>
      <mrow>      \abs{-\tfrac1x }\amp \lt \eps</mrow>
      <mrow>      \abs{x}\amp \gt \tfrac{1}{\eps}.</mrow>
    </md>
</p>
<p>
    Thus <m>   x\gt \tfrac{1}{\eps}</m>, and
     it appears that <m>\abs{f(x)-1}\lt\eps</m> as long as
    <m>x</m> is greater than <m>\frac{1}{\eps}.</m> 
</p>
<p>
<alert>END OF SCRAPWORK</alert>
</p>
      </investigation>

  <proof>
<p>
      Let <m>\eps>0</m> be given.  Take <m>x>B=1/\eps</m>. Then
      <md>
<mrow>
        \abs{\tfrac{1}{x}}\amp \lt \eps</mrow>
<mrow>        \abs{\tfrac{-1}{x}}\amp\lt \eps</mrow>
<mrow>        \abs{\left(1-\tfrac{1}{x}\right)-1}\amp\lt \eps</mrow>
<mrow>        \abs{f(x)-1}\amp\lt \eps.</mrow>
</md>

      Therefore by <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-posinfinity"></xref>,
      <me>
      \limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=1.
      </me>
    </p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>

<example>
<!-- <title></title> -->
<p>
In <xref ref="SECTIONhoriz-asympt-as"></xref> we approached the problem of
finding  a horizontal asymptote of
<m>f(x)=\frac{5x}{x+1}</m> in the following highly intuitive manner, using
the <q><m>\approach{\infty}</m></q> notation.
<md>
<mrow>\limit{x}{\infty}{\frac{5x}{x+1}} =
\limit{x}{\infty}{\frac{5x}{x\left(1+\frac1x\right)}}\amp{} =
  \limit{x}{\infty}{\frac{5}{1+\frac1x}}
</mrow>
<mrow>
\amp{}=
  \frac{5}{1+\frac{1}{\approach{\infty}}}=\frac{5}{1+0}=5.
</mrow>
  </md>
  So we see that this limit must be equal to five. To prove this
  rigorously, without referring to infinity, we use
  <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-posinfinity"></xref>
</p>
</example>
<investigation>
<p>

  Let <m>\eps\gt0 </m> be given. As before we
   work backwards from our goal, <m>\abs{\frac{5x}{x+1}-5}\lt\eps</m>.

<md>
<mrow>
    \abs{\frac{5x}{x+1}-5}\amp\lt\eps
</mrow>
<mrow>\abs{\frac{5x-5(x+1)}{x+1}}\amp\lt \eps</mrow>
<mrow>\abs{\frac{-5}{x+1}}\amp\lt\eps</mrow>
<mrow>\frac{\abs{-5}}{\abs{x+1}}\amp\lt\eps.</mrow>
</md>
As long as <m>x\gt-1</m> this is the same as 

<men  xml:id="EQUATIONLimAtInfExample1">
\frac{5}{x+1}\lt\eps,
</men>

  so we will stipulate that <m>B</m> (and therefore <m>x</m>) must be  at least greater than <m>-1</m>.
  Solving <xref ref="EQUATIONLimAtInfExample1">equation</xref> for
  <m>x</m> we see that
  <m>
  x\gt \frac5\eps-1
  </m>
  also.
  So we take <m>B</m> to be the greater of <m>-1</m> and <m>\frac5\eps-1</m>. We capture
  this idea with the notation,  <m>B=\max\left(-1, \frac5\eps-1\right)</m>.
</p>
<p>
<alert>END OF SCRAPWORK</alert>
</p>
</investigation>

<problem>
  <introduction>
