<section xml:id="SECTIONlimits-at-real">
<title>Limits at a Real Number</title>

<p>
In the previous section we
were focused on the relatively simple limits associated with
horizontal asymptotes.  But our goal is to use the limit in
<xref ref="DEFINITIONDerivative"></xref> to prove that the Differentiation
Rules we<rsq/>ve been using are valid. To do that we will use the following
precise, rigorous definition of a limit as <m>x\rightarrow a</m> where <m>a</m>
is some real number.
</p>

<definition xml:id="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real">
<title>The Limit at a Point</title>
<statement>
<p>
  <!-- \label{def:limits-at-real} -->
  Suppose <m>f(x)</m> is  a function, and that <m>a</m> is a real number. We  say that
  <me>
  \limit{x}{a}{f(x)}=L
  </me>
  if and only if for every <m>\eps\gt 0</m> there is a <m>\delta\gt 0</m> with the property
  that whenever <m>0\lt\abs{x-a}\lt \delta</m>, <m>\abs{f(x)-L}\lt \eps</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<p>
Take particular notice of the fact that neither <xref
ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-posinfinity">Definition</xref> nor <xref
ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref> tells us how to compute the
limit. They serve only to rigorously establish what our intuition says
the limit should be.
</p>

<!-- <!-\- <aside> -\-> -->
<!-- <!-\- <title>Note to self</title> -\-> -->
<!-- <!-\- <p> -\-> -->
<!-- <!-\- Digression missing -\-> -->
<!-- <!-\- </p> -\-> -->
<!-- <!-\- </aside> -\-> -->

<paragraphs  xml:id="DIGRESSIONAbsoluteValue2">
<title>DIGRESSION: The Absolute Value, again</title>


<!-- \begin{Digression}[The Absolute Value, again] -->
<!--   \label{digression:AbsoluteValue2} -->
<p>
  It can be difficult to work with the absolute value
  inside of inequalities. To avoid these kinds of problems it is
  useful to remember that
    <mdn>
    <!-- \label{eq:AltDefAbsVal} -->
<mrow  xml:id="EQUATIONAltDefAbsVal">    \abs{A}\amp{}\le B \amp{}\amp{}\text{ if and only if } \amp{}-B\le A\le B.</mrow>
    </mdn>
  Although the second version looks slightly more complicated, it has the
  advantage that there are no absolute value symbols to trip us up.
</p>
<!-- \end{Digression} -->
<p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
</paragraphs>

<p>
Notice the similarities and the differences between
<xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-posinfinity"></xref>, <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-neginfinity"></xref>, and <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref>.
</p>
        
<p>
We use  <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref> the same way we used
<xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-posinfinity">Definition</xref>: We take <m>\eps\gt0</m> as a
challenge and find conditions which guarantee that
<m>\abs{f(x)-L}\lt\eps</m>. Previously we were interested in the behavior
of <m>f(x)</m> <q>close to infinity</q> so the condition was that <m>x\gt B</m>
(that <m>x</m> was large enough, loosely speaking). Now we are interested
in the behavior of <m>f(x)</m> <q>close to <m>a</m></q> so we
need to
indicate how close <m>x</m> has to be to <m>a</m>.  The <m>\delta\gt0</m> in
<xref ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref> plays the same role that the
upper bound <m>B</m> played in <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-posinfinity"></xref> and
<xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-neginfinity"></xref>. It locates where <m>x</m> must be in
order to guarantee that <m>\abs{f(x)-L}\lt\eps</m>.
</p>

<!-- <figure> -->
<!-- <caption> -->
<!-- <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q.E.D." visual="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q.E.D.">This figure needs a caption.</url> -->
<!-- </caption> -->

<!-- </figure> -->
<!-- \begin{wrapfigure}[6]{r}{1.2in} -->
<!--   \captionsetup{labelformat=empty} -->
<!--   \vskip-6mm -->
<!--   \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1in,width=1.2in]{../Figures/EpsDelta2}} -->
<!--   \label{fig:EpsDelta2} -->
<!-- \end{wrapfigure} -->
<p>
The sketch below  depicts the situation when
<m>\limit{x}{a}{f(x)}=L</m> visually.  We have indicated that <m>f(x)</m> is not defined at <m>a</m>, but it
could be. Limits don<rsq/>t care what happens at <m>a</m>, only what
happens near <m>a</m>. To emphasize this point we will usually say that
<m>0\lt\abs{x-a}\lt\delta</m>, rather than <m>\abs{x-a}\lt\delta</m>. Because
the inequality on the left is strict, we do not consider what happens
when <m>x=a</m>.
</p>

<aside>
<title>Comment</title>
<p>
The graph
of <m>f(x)</m> appears to be a straight line because we are zoomed in very
close to the point <m>(a,L)</m> and the Principle of Local Linearity is in
play.
</p>
</aside>

<image source="images/EpsDelta2.png" width="30%"/>

<p>
As before <m>\eps </m> is the challenge. To show that the limit exists and
is equal to <m>L</m> as claimed our task is to
find a value of <m>\delta</m> such that, as long
<!-- \aside{More succinctly: -->
<!--   <m>0\lt\abs{x-a}\lt\delta</m>.} -->
 as
<m>% \overbrace{x \text{ is between } a-\delta \text{ and }a+\delta}^{x
% \text{ is  within } \delta \text{ of } a, x\neq a}
x 
</m>
 is between <m> a-\delta \text{ and }a+\delta</m>
the corresponding
<!-- \aside{More succinctly: <m>\abs{f(x)-L}\lt\eps</m>.} -->
<!-- <me>\underbrace{\overbrace{f(x) \text{ will be between } -->
<!--    L-\eps \text{ and }L+\eps}^{f(x) \text{ is within } \eps \text{ of } -->
<!--    L}}_{\text{More succinctly, } \abs{f(x)-L}\lt\eps} -->
<!-- </me>. -->
<m>f(x)</m> will be between <m>L-\eps </m> and <m>L+\eps </m>. 
</p>
<p>
More succinctly, we need to find <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that if <m>0\lt\abs{x-a}\lt\delta</m> then <m>\abs{f(x)-L}\lt\eps</m>.
</p>
<p>
Visually, this means that  the graph of <m>f(x)</m> will be
between the dashed horizontal lines as long as <m>x</m> is between the
dotted vertical lines.
</p>
<p>


<xref ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref> is the culmination of
approximately <m>200</m> years of attempts by some very brilliant people to
provide a rigorous foundation for Calculus. Don<rsq/>t expect to absorb
this easily. It will take time and effort to fully understand and be
able to use it.  We will start simply.
</p>

<exercise xml:id="DRILLLimAtZero-LimAtA">
<statement>
<p>
  <!-- \label{drill:LimAtZero-LimAtA} -->
  Use 
  <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-infinity-nearly-adequate"></xref>, <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-posinfinity"></xref>, 
  <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-neginfinity"></xref>, and <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref> to
  explain that the following are <q>obviously</q> true.
 <me>\limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=L \text{ if and only if }
 \limit{x}{\infty}{(f(x)-L)}=0.</me>
 <me>\limit{x}{-\infty}{f(x)}=L\text{ if and only if
 }\limit{x}{-\infty}{(f(x)-L)}=0.</me>
 <me>\limit{x}{a}{f(x)}=L\text{ if and only if
 }\limit{x}{a}{(f(x)-L)}=0.</me>
We are not looking for a formal proof, just a reasonable
  explanation.
</p>
</statement>
</exercise>



<example>
<p>
 Observe that it is intuitively clear that if <m>f(x)=-x^2+2</m> then
 <m>\limit{x}{0}{f(x)}=2</m>. We wish to prove this rigorously.
</p>
</example>
  <investigation>
<p>

    Suppose <m>\eps\gt0</m> is given.
    Our goal is to find a <m>\delta\gt0</m> such that if
    <m>0\lt\abs{x-0}\lt\delta</m> (or just <m>0\lt\abs{x}\lt\delta</m>) then <m>
   p \abs{f(x)-2}\lt \eps</m>.
Solving this for <m>x</m> we have
    <md>
<mrow>
      \abs{-x^2+2-2}\amp \lt \eps
</mrow>
<mrow>      \abs{-x^2}\amp \lt \eps</mrow>
<mrow>      \abs{x^2}\amp \lt \eps.</mrow>
</md>

    Recall from <xref ref="DIGRESSIONAbsValSqrt"></xref> that
    <m>\sqrt{x^2}=\abs{x}</m>, so we see that <m> \abs{x}\lt \sqrt{\eps} </m>
    or, equivalently
    <me>
      -\sqrt{\eps}\lt x\lt \sqrt{\eps}.
      </me>
</p>
<p>
      
      It appears that <m> \abs{f(x)-2}\lt \eps</m> as long as
      <m> \abs{x}\lt \sqrt{\eps}</m>, so we take <m> \delta=\sqrt{\eps}</m>.
</p>
<p>
<alert>END OF SCRAPWORK</alert>
</p>
   </investigation>
<p>

   This was the scrapwork. The proof consists of showing that the
   condition we found, <m>\abs{x}\lt\delta(=\sqrt{\eps})</m>, actually
   works.
</p>

  <proof>
<p>
    Let <m>\eps\gt 0</m> be given. Take <m>\delta=\sqrt{\eps}\gt0</m>.
</p>
<p>

    Assume that <m>0\lt \abs{x}\lt \delta</m>.  Then
    \begin{align*}
      \abs{x}\amp \lt \delta
      \sqrt{x^2}\amp \lt \sqrt{\eps}
      x^2 \amp \lt \eps
      \abs{-x^2} \amp \lt \eps
      \abs{-x^2+2-2} \amp \lt \eps
      \abs{f(x)-2} \amp \lt \eps.
    \end{align*}
    Therefore <m>\limit{x}{0}{f(x)}=2</m>.
</p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>

<p>

  Notice that our proof does not give us any new information since
    it is intuitively clear that <m>\limit{x}{0}{(-x^2+2)}=2</m>. The formalism of
    a limit merely confirms, in a manner even Bishop Berkeley would
    accept, what we already know to be true.
</p>
<p>
 
    Incidentally, since <m>f(0)=-0^2+2=2</m> we have also just proved that
    <m>f(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=0</m>. See <xref ref="DEFINITIONcontinuity"></xref>.
</p>
<p>



  For simple problems like this one the proof consisted of writing the
  algebraic steps from our <term>Scrapwork</term>  backwards, as you see. This
  worked because every algebraic step in the <term>Scrapwork</term>  was
  reversible. But don<rsq/>t jump to conclusions. This will not always be
  the case.
</p>
<p>

  Clearly the <term>Scrapwork</term>  is the most important part of the solution
  process for this problem. In a very real sense it actually is the
  solution. We call it <term>Scrapwork</term>  because it is the part of the work
  that you don<rsq/>t show anyone else because it is messy and not well
  organized\aside{We kept it clean and orderly here so you could see
    the reasoning.}.  The scrapwork is like the scaffolding used to
  construct a building. The proof is the building.
</p>
<p>

  It is absolutely necessary to have the scaffolding while
  construction is ongoing but you tear it down and clean everything up
  before you move in. In the same way your proof should be a cleaned
  up version of your scrapwork.  If this example were a homework
  problem, your solution would be the part that appears between
  <alert>Proof</alert> and the little black square, <m>\halmos</m>, at the end.
</p>



<aside>
<title>Historical Background</title>
<p>
When Latin
  was the language of scholarship a mathematical proof ended with the
  letters <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q.E.D."
  visual="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q.E.D."><foreign>Q.E.D.</foreign></url>,
  which are the initials of the phrase <foreign>quod erat
  demonstrandum</foreign>, meaning <q>which was to be demonstrated.</q>
  Contrary to a popular joke it does not mean <q>Quite Easily
  Done.</q> In the late twentieth century this traditional ending
  began to be replaced by the black square we<rsq/>re using (or some
  variation of it). It is called a <q>Halmos</q> in honor of
  <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Halmos/" visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Halmos/">Paul
  Halmos</url>, a preeminent mathematician of the <m>20</m>th century, who
  popularized it. 
</p>
</aside>




<example xml:id="example:DiscontLimit2">
<p>
  <!-- \label{example:DiscontLimit2} -->
Returning <xref ref="EXAMPLEDiscontLimit1"></xref> from
<xref ref="SECTIONlimit-theorems-laws"></xref>   recall that we had
<me>
  f(x)=
  \begin{cases}
    3x \amp  \text{if } x\neq2
    10  \amp  \text{if } x=2.
  \end{cases}
  </me>
  We had shown by an intuitive argument that <m>\limit{x}{2}{f(x)}= 6</m>.
  Our previous proof lacked rigor, especially in the last step. We
  will provide a fully rigorous proof now.
</p>
</example>

  <proof>
<p>
    Let <m>\eps>0</m> be given and take <m>0\lt\delta\lt\frac{\eps}{3}</m>. Then if
    <m>0\lt \abs{x-2}\lt\delta</m> we have
    <md>
<mrow>
      -\delta\amp \lt x-2 \lt\delta
</mrow>
<mrow>
      -\frac{\eps}{3}\amp \lt x-2 \lt\frac{\eps}{3}
</mrow>
<mrow> 
      -\eps\amp \lt 3x-6 \lt\eps.
</mrow>
</md>
Observe that <m>f(x)=3x</m> since <m>x\neq2</m>. Therefore 
<me>      -\eps \lt f(x)-6 \lt\eps</me>
    and so
    <me>\abs{f(x)-6}\lt\eps.</me>
Therefore <m>\tlimit{x}{2}{f(x)}=6.</m>
</p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>
<p>
 Notice that it is again irrelevant that <m>f(2)=10</m>.
</p>
<problem>
<statement>
<p>
  Use the proof above to recreate the scrapwork that we did before we
  wrote the proof.
</p>
</statement>
</problem>




<example xml:id="EXAMPLEConcrete1">
<title>4</title>

  <!-- \label{example:Concrete1} -->
<p>

 We would like to find the value of
  <m>\limit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x-1}}</m>, and prove that the value
  we find is correct.
</p>
<p>
   
 Remember that none of our limit definitions tell us how to find the
  value of a limit, only how to prove that it has a particular value
  after we<rsq/>ve found it. In our examples so far the value of the limits
  have been intuitively clear so we haven<rsq/>t concerned ourselves with
  this part of the problem.  But before we can prove that a limit has
  a particular value we obviously need to decide what we believe the
  limit value is.
</p>
<p>

  We have several options for doing this. The simplest is guessing,
  but guessing works best if we have some intuition about the problem.
  Guessing blindly is usually a waste of time. Nevertheless, guessing is
  always an option. Can you guess the value of this limit?
</p>
<p>
  
  Another simple option is to use a calculator and plug the value of
  the limit point, in this case <m>x=\frac12</m>, and see what the
  calculator comes up with. This will work if the function is
  continuous at the limit point. But <m>\frac{4x^2-1}{2x-1}</m> is not
continuous at <m>x=\frac12</m> so that won<rsq/>t help with this problem. Try it
and see.
</p>

<image source="images/EpsDelta4.png" width="30%"/>
<!-- \begin{wrapfigure}[]{r}{1.8in} -->
<!--     \captionsetup{labelformat=empty} -->
<!--     \vskip-3mm -->
<!--     \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1.8in,width=1.8in]{../Figures/EpsDelta4}} -->
<!--     \label{fig:EpsDelta4} -->
<!--   \end{wrapfigure} -->
<p>
A third, and much more useful option is to sketch the graph of <m>f(x)</m>
to see what <m>f(x)</m> is close to near the limit point.  The graph of
<m>f(x)=\frac{4x^2-1}{2x-1}</m> is given at the right. It is not defined at
<m>x=1/2</m> because when <m>x=1/2</m> we get zero in the
denominator. Nevertheless the limit at <m>x=1/2</m> seems to exist. As you
can see as <m>x</m> approaches <m>1/2</m>, <m>f(x)</m> appears to approach <m>2</m>. Based
on this graph it seems likely that the value of the limit is <m>2</m>.
</p>
<p>
As we saw in <xref ref="CHAPTERlimits-lhop-rule"></xref>, Algebra can also be
very helpful. In this case we see that
  <me>
  \frac{4x^2-1}{2x-1}= {\frac{(2x+1)(2x-1)}{2x-1}}=
  (2x+1)\cdot\CancelToRed{=1}{\frac{2x-1}{2x-1}}=
  (2x+1)
  </me>
  where the cancellation in red is only valid when <m>x\neq\frac12</m>,
  our limit point is <m>x=\frac12</m> so it is not under consideration.
</p>
<p>
  In fact, once we have rigorously proved <xref ref="THEOREMLimProd2"></xref>, and
  <xref ref="THEOREMConstLimit"></xref> from
  <xref ref="SECTIONlimit-theorems-laws"></xref> (We will do this in
  <xref ref="SECTIONLimitLaws"></xref>)
the following will be a valid
  proof:

<md>
<mrow>\limit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x-1}}\amp =
    \limit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{(2x+1)(2x-1)}{2x-1}}</mrow>
<mrow>\amp =
  \left[\limit{x}{\frac12}{(2x+1)}\right]\left[\limit{x}{\frac12}{\CancelToRed{=1}{\frac{2x-1}{2x-1}}}\
    \ \ \ \ \ \right]</mrow>
<mrow>\amp =
    \limit{x}{\frac12}{(2x+1)}
    </mrow>
<mrow>    \amp = 2.
</mrow>
</md>
</p>





</example>
  <problem>
<statement>
<p>
    Identify where we used <xref ref="THEOREMLimSum2"></xref>,
    <xref ref="THEOREMLimProd2"></xref>, and
    <xref ref="THEOREMConstLimit"></xref> in the development above.
  </p>
</statement>
</problem>
<p>

  Because we haven<rsq/>t yet rigorously proved
  <xref ref="THEOREMLimSum2"></xref>, <xref  ref="THEOREMLimProd2"></xref>, or <xref ref="THEOREMConstLimit"></xref> we
  can<rsq/>t use them to construct a rigorous proof. Until they are proved
  they are not known, they are just believed. Belief is not knowledge.
</p>
<p>

  But there is no problem with using them to gather evidence.
  So far we have strong evidence that this limit is <m>2</m>.
</p>
<p>

Having gathered our evidence, we now believe that <m>
\limit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x-1}}=2</m>. Next we need to do the
scrapwork for our proof.
</p>

<investigation>
<p>
As always we work backwards from our
goal. We need to show that   <m>\abs{f(x)-2}\lt \eps</m> so
<me>\abs{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x-1}-2} \lt \eps.</me>
Since we<rsq/>re not interested in the value of anything
  at <m>x=\frac12</m> (where the denominator is zero) we can factor and cancel, giving

<md>
<mrow>\abs{\frac{(2x+1)\cancel{(2x-1)}}{\cancel{2x-1}}-2}\amp \lt \eps</mrow>
<mrow>\abs{2x+1-2}\amp \lt \eps</mrow>
<mrow>\abs{2x-1}  \amp \lt \eps.</mrow>
</md>

  We see that if  <m>\abs{2x-1}  \lt \eps</m> then
    <me>
    -\eps \lt 2x-1  \lt \eps
    </me>
    or
    <me>
    \frac12-\frac{\eps}{2}\lt x\lt \frac12+\frac{\eps}{2}.
    </me>
    So  taking <m>\delta=\frac{\eps}{2}</m> will work for this problem.
</p>
<p>
<alert>END OF SCRAPWORK</alert>
</p>
</investigation>

<proof>
<p>
  Let <m>\eps>0</m> be given. Take <m>\delta=\frac{\eps}{2}\gt0</m>.  Then if <m>0\lt\abs{x-\frac12}\lt\delta</m> we have

<md>
<mrow>    \abs{x-\frac12}\amp \lt\frac{\eps}{2}</mrow>
<mrow>-\frac{\eps}{2}\lt    x-\frac12\amp \lt\frac{\eps}{2}</mrow>
<mrow>-\eps \lt 2x-1  \amp \lt \eps</mrow>
<mrow>-\eps \lt 2x+1-2  \amp \lt \eps.</mrow>
</md>
Since <m>x\neq\frac12</m> we see that

<md>
<mrow>-\eps \lt \frac{(2x+1)(2x-1)}{2x-1} -2 \amp \lt \eps</mrow>
<mrow>-\eps \lt \frac{4x^2-1}{2x+1} -2 \amp \lt \eps</mrow>
<mrow>-\eps \lt f(x) -2 \amp \lt \eps,</mrow>
</md>
  and so
  <me>
  \abs{f(x)-2}\lt\eps.
  </me>

  Therefore <me>\limit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x+1}}=2</me>.
</p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>

<p>
  A long list of inequalities like those above can be a little
  intimidating. Don<rsq/>t let that stop you. Verify each transition from
  one inequality to the other. If you don<rsq/>t see why a particular
  transition  is valid refer back to the scrapwork.
</p>



<paragraphs  xml:id="DIGRESSIONWhyProveTheorems">
<title>DIGRESSION: Why We Prove Theorems </title>


<!-- \begin{Digression}[Why We Prove Theorems] -->
<!--   \label{digression:WhyProveTheorems} -->
<p>
  The proof of any theorem will follow logically from the relevant
  definitions. However, as we<rsq/>ve seen proving that
  <m>\limit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x+1}}=2</m> from
  <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref> was very delicate and
  troublesome. We<rsq/>d really like to avoid this if we can.
</p>
<p>

  We prove general theorems so that we can use them as tools. Do we
  have any tools (theorems) that would have made the proof of
  <me>\limit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x+1}}=2</me> simpler?
</p>
                  
<problem>
<introduction>
<p>
</p>
</introduction>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Show that <m>\tlimit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x+1}}</m>
      satisfies all of the conditions of <xref ref="THEOREMLHRuleGen"></xref>.
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Use <xref ref="THEOREMLHRuleGen"> </xref> to prove that
      <m>\tlimit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x+1}}=2</m>.
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
<statement>
<p>
 Explain your proof in part (b) is rigorous.
    </p>
</statement>
</task>
</problem>
<!-- \begin{embeddedproblem-enumerate} -->
<!--     \begin{enumerate}[label={  (\alph* )}] -->
<!--     \item Show that <m>\tlimit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x+1}}</m> -->
<!--       satisfies all of the conditions of <xref ref="THEOREMthm:LHRuleGen"></xref>. -->
<!--     \item Use Theorem~\ref{thm:LHRuleGen} to prove that -->
<!--       <m>\tlimit{x}{\frac12}{\frac{4x^2-1}{2x+1}}=2</m>. -->
<!--     \item Explain your proof in part (b) is rigorous. -->
<!--     \end{enumerate} -->
<!--   \end{embeddedproblem-enumerate} -->

<p>
  \lhop<rsq/>s Rule is a very powerful tool which simultaneously
  evaluates a limit and provides a rigorous proof of the result. And
  it is much easier to use than
  <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref>.
</p>
<p>

  But sadly, it will be of no use to us for the remainder of this
  chapter. \lhop<rsq/>s  Rule relies on knowing that our differentiation rules
  are valid, and we don<rsq/>t know that yet. That the differentiation rules
  are valid is  exactly what  we are trying to show. To use
  \lhop <rsq/>s Rule would be to engage in  circular reasoning, which is invalid.
</p>
<!-- \end{Digression} -->
<p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
</paragraphs>

<example>
<p>
  In this example we will show rigorously that the derivative of
  <m>f(x)=x^2</m> is <m>f^\prime(x)=2x</m>. To do that we need to show that
  <me>
  \limit{h}{0}{\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}} = 2x.
  </me>
  Recall that differentiation is a local property so we are thinking
  of <m>x</m> as a fixed, but unspecified real number. The variable in this
  example is <m>h</m>.
</p>
</example>
              
  <investigation>
    <p>
    For <m>\eps\gt0</m> we need to find <m>\delta\gt 0</m> such that if
    <m>0\lt\abs{h}\lt\delta</m>, then <m>\abs{\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}-2x}\lt
    \eps</m>.
    Working backwards from this we have
    <md>
<mrow>
      \abs{\frac{(x+h)^2-x^2}{h}-2x}\amp\lt\eps
</mrow>
<mrow>      \abs{\frac{x^2+2xh+h^2-x^2}{h}-2x}\amp\lt\eps</mrow>
<mrow>      \abs{\frac{2xh+h^2}{h}-2x}\amp\lt\eps</mrow>
<mrow>      \abs{2x+h-2x}\amp\lt\eps</mrow>
<mrow>      \abs{h}      \amp\lt\eps</mrow>
<mrow>      -\eps\lt h      \amp\lt\eps,</mrow>
</md>

    so we choose <m>\delta=\eps</m>.
    </p>
<p>
<alert>END OF SCRAPWORK</alert>
</p>
  </investigation>
<problem>
<statement>
<p>
  Use the scrapwork above to write down a rigorous proof  that if <m>f(x)=x^2</m> then
  <m>f^\prime(x)=2x</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</problem>
 
</section>



<section xml:id="SECTIONLimitLaws">
<title>Limit Laws (Theorems)</title>

<introduction>

<p>
If we can prove each of the limit laws in
<xref ref="CHAPTERdiff-rules-with-limits">Chapter</xref> rigorously (i.e, using
<xref ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref>) we will have provided a
rigorous foundation for Differential Calculus. We will address these
now.
</p>
<p>

To prove the limit laws we will need to make extensive use of what is
called the <term>Triangle Inequality</term>. We  state and prove the
Triangle Inequality here so that we can cite it as needed.
</p>

  <theorem xml:id="THEOREMTriangIneq">
<title>The Triangle Inequality</title>
<p>
    <!-- \label{THEOREMTriangIneq} -->
    For any real numbers <m>x</m>, and <m>y</m>, <m>\abs{x+y} \leq
    \abs{x}+\abs{y}</m>.
  </p>
</theorem>

<p>
  The proof of the Triangle Inequality relies on
  <xref ref="EQUATIONAltDefAbsVal"></xref>)
  from
  <xref ref="DIGRESSIONAbsoluteValue2" text="custom">Digression: Absolute Value, again</xref>.
</p>

<proof  xml:id="PROOFTriIneq">
<title>Proof of the Triangle Inequality</title>
<p>
  Clearly <m>-\abs{x}\leq x \leq \abs{x}</m> and <m>-\abs{y}\leq y \leq
  \abs{y}.</m> Adding these together we have
  <md>
<mrow>

    -\abs{x}-\abs{y}\amp\leq x+y\leq \abs{x}+\abs{y}
</mrow>
<mrow>    \underbrace{-\left(\abs{x}+\abs{y}\right)}_{-B}\amp\leq    \underbrace{x+y}_A \leq \underbrace{\abs{x}+\abs{y}}_{B}.</mrow>
</md>
  so by <xref ref="EQUATIONAltDefAbsVal"></xref>) we have <m>\abs{x+y} \leq \abs{x}+\abs{y}</m>.
</p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>


<p>
The Limit Laws we need to prove are:
<dl>
<li>
<title><xref ref="THEOREMConstLimit">Theorem</xref>:</title>
<p>
  The Limit of a Constant is the  Constant.
</p>
</li>
<li>
<title> <xref ref="THEOREMLimSum2">Theorem</xref>:</title>
<p>
 The Limit of a Sum is the Sum of the  Limits
</p>
</li>
<li>
<title><xref ref="THEOREMLimProd2">Theorem</xref>:</title>
<p>
 The Limit of a Product is the  Product of the Limits
</p>
</li>
<li>
<title><xref ref="THEOREMCompositionLimit">Theorem</xref>:</title>
<p>
 The Limit of a Composition  is the Composition of the Limits, and
</p>
</li>
<li>
<title><xref ref="THEOREMFiniteSqueeze">Theorem</xref>:</title>
<p>
The  Squeeze Theorem
</p>
</li>
</dl>

</p>
<p>
We will provide a proof of the <q>limit at infinity</q> version of each
of these Theorems using <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimit-at-posinfinity"></xref>.
We will leave the proof of the <q>limit at a real number</q> version
using the <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref> as an exercise for
you.  In every case you can model your scrapwork and proof on the ones
we provide.
</p>
<theorem xml:id="THEOREMLimConstInf">
<title>The Limit at Infinity of a Constant Function is the Constant</title>
<p>
  Suppose <m>L</m> and <m>K</m> are real numbers.  If <m>f(x)=K</m> for all <m>x\gt L</m>
  then <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=K</m>.
</p>
</theorem>

<proof>
<p>
  Let <m>\eps\gt 0</m> be given. Take <m>B=L.</m> Then if <m>x\gt B</m> we see that
  <me>
  \abs{f(x)-K}=\abs{K-K}=0\lt \eps.
  </me>
  Therefore <me>\limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=K.</me>
</p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>
<p>
The formalism we<rsq/>re using requires that we specify some value for
<m>B</m>. It was convenient to specify <m>B=L</m>, but in this proof any value
for <m>B\ge L</m> would have worked as well.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="THEOREMLimConstNegInf">
<title>The Limit at Negative Infinity of a Constant Function is the Constant</title>
<p>
  Suppose <m>U</m> and <m>K</m> are real numbers.  If <m>f(x)=K</m> for all <m>x\lt U</m>
  then <m>\limit{x}{-\infty}{f(x)}=K.</m>
</p>
</theorem>


<problem>
<statement>
<p>
  Use the proof of <xref ref="THEOREMLimConstInf">Theorem</xref> as a model to construct
  a proof of   <xref ref="THEOREMLimConstNegInf"></xref>.
</p>
</statement>
</problem>


<theorem xml:id="THEOREMLimConstPoint">
<title>The Limit at a Point of a Constant Function is the Constant</title>
<p>
Suppose <m>K</m> is a real number and <m>a</m> is a point in the domain of
<m>f(x)</m> .  If <m>f(x)=K</m> near <m>a</m>
then <m>\limit{x}{a}{f(x)}=K.</m>
</p>
</theorem>


<problem>
<statement>
<p>
  Use the proof of <xref ref="THEOREMLimConstInf">Theorem</xref> as a model to construct
  a proof of   <xref ref="THEOREMLimConstPoint"></xref>.
</p>
</statement>
<hint>
<p>
Despite the apparent simplicity of this problem there is a lot
  going on here. Recall that <q>near</q> means that <m>f(x)=K</m> on some open
  interval, say <m>(c,d)</m>, containing <m>a</m> except possibly at <m>a</m> (see
  <xref ref="DEFINITIONnear">Definition</xref>). You need to find a <m>\delta\gt0</m> such
  that if <m>-\delta\lt x-a \lt\delta</m> then <m>f(x)=K</m>. That is, you need
  an interval of length <m>2\delta</m> with <m>a</m> as the midpoint where
  <m>f(x)=K</m>. But there is no guarantee that <m>a</m> is the midpoint of the
  interval <m>(c,d)</m>. This would be an excellent time to engage your
  visual intuition by drawing a sketch so you can <q>see</q> the
  problem.
</p>
</hint>

</problem>
</introduction>

<subsection xml:id="SUBSECTIONlimit-sum-at">
<title>The Limit of a Sum</title>

  <theorem xml:id="THEOREMLimSumInf">
<title>The Limit of a Sum at Infinity</title>
<p>
    <!-- \label{THEOREMLimSumInf} -->
  If <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=L_f</m> and <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}=L_g</m> then
  <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{\left(f(x)+g(x)\right)}=L_f+L_g.</m>
</p>
</theorem>

<investigation>
<p>
  As always  we begin by assuming that <m>\eps\gt 0</m> has been given.
</p>
<p>

  We want to show that if <m>x</m> is large enough (larger than some
  specified <m>B</m>) then
  <men  xml:id="EQUATIONDerivSumInf">
    <!-- \label{eq:DerivSumInf} -->
    \abs{(\textcolor{red}{f(x)}
      +\textcolor{blue}{g(x)})-(\textcolor{red}{L_f}+\textcolor{blue}{L_g})}\lt \eps.
</men>
   The only information we have to work with is the knowledge that
  <me>
  \limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=L_f\text{ and
  }\limit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}=L_g,
  </me>
which means that we can make <m>\abs{f(x)-L_f}</m> and <m>\abs{g(x)-L_g}</m>
  as close to zero as we wish, provided we make <m>x</m> large enough.
Rewriting the left-hand side of <xref ref="EQUATIONDerivSumInf">Equation</xref> and
invoking the Triangle Inequality we see that
<md>
  <mrow>
    \abs{(\textcolor{red}{f(x)}
    +\textcolor{blue}{g(x)})-(\textcolor{red}{L_f}+\textcolor{blue}{L_g})}
    \amp =
  \abs{(\textcolor{red}{f(x)}-\textcolor{red}{L_f})+(
  \textcolor{blue}{g(x)}-\textcolor{blue}{L_g})}
  </mrow>
  <mrow>
    \amp \le  \abs{\textcolor{red}{f(x)}-\textcolor{red}{L_f}}+\abs{
    \textcolor{blue}{g(x)}-\textcolor{blue}{L_g}}.
  </mrow>
</md>

But as we<rsq/>ve observed we can make <m>\abs{f(x)-L_f}</m> and
<m>\abs{g(x)-L_g}</m> as close to zero as we wish, provided we take <m>x</m>
large enough. To be precise, there is a number <m>B_f</m> such that if
<m>x\gt B_f</m> then <m>\abs{f(x)-L_f}\lt\frac{\eps}{2}</m>. Similarly there is a number <m>B_g</m> such
that if <m>x\gt B_g</m> then <m>\abs{g(x)-L_f}\lt\frac{\eps}{2}</m>.
</p>
<p>

Since we need for both of these things to happen a sufficiently large
value of <m>x</m> is one where <m>x\gt B_f</m> and <m>x\gt B_g</m>.
</p>
<p>
<alert>END OF SCRAPWORK</alert>
</p>
</investigation>

<proof>
<p>
  Let <m>\eps\gt 0</m> be given.

  Since <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)}=L_f</m> there is a bound, <m>B_f</m> such
  that if <m>x\gt B_f</m> then <m>\abs{f(x)-L_f}\lt \frac{\eps}{2}.</m>

  Since <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}=L_g</m> there is a bound, <m>B_g</m> such
  that if <m>x\gt B_g</m> then <m>\abs{g(x)-L_g}\lt \frac{\eps}{2}.</m>

  Take <m>B= \max(B_f,B_g)</m>. Then if <m>x\gt B</m> then
  <m>x\gt B_f</m> and <m>x\gt B_g</m>. Thus by the Triangle Inequality
  (<xref ref="THEOREMTriangIneq"></xref>)
  <md>
<mrow>
    \abs{(f(x)+g(x))-(L_f+L_g)}\amp =    \abs{(f(x)-L_f)+(g(x)-L_g)}
</mrow>
<mrow>    \amp \le {\abs{f(x)-L_f}}+{\abs{g(x)-L_g}}</mrow>
<mrow>    \amp \lt \frac{\eps}{2} +</mrow>
<mrow>    \frac{\eps}{2}    \amp= \eps.</mrow>
</md>


  Therefore <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{\left(f(x)+g(x)\right)}=L_f+L_g.</m>
</p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>


<problem>
<statement>
<p>
  Use the proof of <xref ref="THEOREMLimSumInf">Theorem</xref> as a model to construct
  a proof of   <xref ref="THEOREMLimSumNegInf"></xref> below.
</p>
</statement>
</problem>

  <theorem xml:id="THEOREMLimSumNegInf">
<title>The Limit of a Sum at Negative Infinity</title>
<p>
    <!-- \label{THEOREMLimSumNegInf} -->
  If <m>\limit{x}{-\infty}{f(x)}=L_f</m> and <m>\limit{x}{-\infty}{g(x)}=L_g</m> then
  <m>\limit{x}{-\infty}{\left(f(x)+g(x)\right)}=L_f+L_g.</m>
</p>
</theorem>





<problem>
<statement>
<p>
  Use the proof of <xref ref="THEOREMLimSumInf">Theorem</xref> as a model to construct
  a proof of   <xref ref="THEOREMLimSumPoint"></xref> below.
</p>
</statement>
</problem>


<theorem xml:id="THEOREMLimSumPoint">
<title>Limit of a Sum at a Point</title>
<p>
Suppose that <m>a</m> is some real number, <m>\limit{x}{a}{f(x)}=L_f</m> and
<m>\limit{x}{a}{g(x)}=L_g</m>. Then
  <me>
  \limit{x}{a}{\left(f(x)+g(x)\right)}=L_f+L_g.
  </me>
</p>
</theorem>



</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="SUBSECTIONsqueeze-theorem">
<title>The Squeeze Theorem</title>

  <theorem xml:id="THEOREMSqThmInfinity">
<title>The Squeeze  Theorem at Infinity</title>
<p>
  If <m>\alpha(x)\le f(x)\le \beta(x)</m> on some
  interval, <m>(c, \infty)</m> and
  <me>
  \limit{x}{\infty}{\alpha(x)} =
  \limit{x}{\infty}{\beta(x)} = L
  </me>
  then <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)} = L</m> also.
</p>
</theorem>


<proof>
<p>
  Let <m>\eps\gt0</m> be given.

  Since <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{\alpha(x)} = L</m> there is some a real number
  <m>B_\alpha</m>, such that if <m>x\gt B_\alpha</m> then
  <m>\abs{\alpha(x)-L}\lt \eps</m>.
  From <xref ref="EQUATIONAltDefAbsVal"></xref>) we see  that for <m>x\gt B_\alpha</m>:
  <me>-\eps \lt  \alpha(x)-L \lt  \eps. </me>  Similarly there
  is a real number <m>B_\beta</m>, such that if <m>x\gt B_\beta</m> then
  <m>\abs{\beta(x)-L}\lt \eps</m>. So for <m>x\gt B_\beta</m>:
  <me>-\eps \lt  \beta(x)-L \lt  \eps. </me>  Take <m>B=\max(c,
  B_\alpha, B_\beta)</m>. Then if
  <m>x\gt B</m>
  <me>
  -\eps \lt  \alpha(x)-L \lt  f(x)-L \lt  \beta(x)-L \lt  \eps.
  </me>
  In particular, <m>  -\eps \lt  f(x)-L \lt  \eps </m> so from
  <xref ref="EQUATIONAltDefAbsVal"></xref>) we see that
  <m>\abs{f(x)-L}\lt \eps </m>.

  Therefore <m>\limit{x}{\infty}{f(x)} = L</m>.
</p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>



<problem>
<statement>
<p>
  Use  the proof of <xref ref="THEOREMSqThmInfinity">Theorem</xref> as a model
  to prove <xref ref="THEOREMSqThmNegInfinity">Theorem</xref> below.
</p>
</statement>
</problem>

  <theorem xml:id="THEOREMSqThmNegInfinity">
<title>The Squeeze  Theorem at Negative Infinity</title>
<p>
  If <me>\alpha(x)\le f(x)\le \beta(x)</me> on some
  interval, <m>(-\infty,c)</m> and
  <me>
  \limit{x}{-\infty}{\alpha(x)} =
  \limit{x}{-\infty}{\beta(x)} = L
  </me>
  then <me>\limit{x}{-\infty}{f(x)} = L</me> also.
</p>
</theorem>



<problem>
<statement>
<p>
  Use  the proof of <xref ref="THEOREMSqThmInfinity">Theorem</xref> as a model
  to prove <xref ref="THEOREMSqThmFinite">Theorem</xref> below.
</p>
</statement>
</problem>

  <theorem xml:id="THEOREMSqThmFinite">
<title>The Squeeze  Theorem, at a Point</title>
<p>
    If <m>\alpha(x)\le f(x)\le \beta(x)</m> near  <m>a</m> and
    <m>\limit{x}{a}{\alpha(x)} = \limit{x}{a}{\beta(x)} = L</m> then
    <m>\limit{x}{a}{f(x)} = L</m> also.
</p>
</theorem>



</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="SECTIONlimit-composition">
<title>The Limit of a Composition</title>

<p>
Recall that at the end of <xref ref="EXAMPLELimComp1"></xref> in
<xref ref="SECTIONmore-indet-forms"></xref> we commented that it is only true that
<m>\tlimit{x}{a}{f(g(x))}</m> is equal
to
<m>f\left(\tlimit{x}{a}{g(x)}\right)</m> when <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>g(a)</m>.
</p>
<p>

The following example demonstrates why we need for  <m>f</m> to be
continuous at  <m>g(a)</m>.
</p>
<example xml:id="EXAMPLELimitComposition">
<p>
  Let <me>f(x)=
  \begin{cases}
    5\amp \text{ if } x\ge1 \\
    0\amp \text{ if } x\lt1
  \end{cases}</me> and  <m>g(x)=\frac{x}{x+1}</m>.
   Observe that
    <m>g(x)\lt
  1</m> when <m>x>0</m>, that
 <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}=1</m>, and that <m>f</m> is not continuous at
 <m>x=1</m>.

 We have <m>f\underbrace{\left(\tlimit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}\right)}_{=1} = f(1) =5</m> and
 <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{f(g(x))} =
 \tlimit{x}{\infty}{f\underbrace{\left(\frac{x}{x+1}\right)}_{\lt1}} =
 0</m>. Therefore
 <me>f\left(\tlimit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}\right)
 \neq\tlimit{x}{\infty}{f(g(x))}.</me>

</p>
</example>


<theorem xml:id="THEOREMLimCompInf">
<title>The Limit of a Composition at Infinity</title>
<p>
  <!-- \label{THEOREMLimCompInf}  -->
  Suppose <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}=L_g</m> and <m>f(y)</m> is continuous at
  <m>y=L_g</m>. Then
  <me>
  \limit{x}{\infty}{f(g(x))} = f(L_g) =
  f\left(\tlimit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}\right).
  </me>
</p>
</theorem>


<investigation>


<!-- <figure> -->
<!-- <caption> -->
<!-- This figure needs a caption.</caption> -->

<!-- </figure> -->
<!-- \begin{wrapfigure}[6]{r}{1.6in} -->
<!--   \captionsetup{labelformat=empty} -->
<!--   \vskip-4mm  -->
<!-- \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1.2in,width=1.6in]{../Figures/LimComp2}} -->
<!-- \label{fig:LimComp2} -->
<!-- \end{wrapfigure} -->
<image source="images/LimComp2.png" width="30%"/>

<p>
It will be  helpful to have a visual guide for this proof so we
will rely on diagrams here in the scrapwork. Our finalized  proof below will not.
</p>
<p>

Let <m>\eps\gt0</m> be given. We need to show that we can find a <m>B\gt0</m>
such that if <m>x\gt B</m> then <m>\abs{f(g(x))-f(L_g)}\lt\eps</m>.
</p>
<p>

Since <m>f</m> is
continuous at <m>y=L_g</m> <xref ref="DEFINITIONcontinuity"></xref> tells us that
<m>\tlimit{y}{L_g}{f(y)}=f(L_g)</m>
</p>
<p>

Thus <xref ref="DEFINITIONlimits-at-real"></xref>  tells us that there
there is a real number <m>\delta>0</m> such that if <m>\abs{y-L_g}\lt\delta</m>
then <m>\abs{f(y)-f(L_g)}\lt\eps</m>, as visualized in the sketch at the
right.
</p>
<p>

Next, consider what it means to say that
<m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}=L_g</m>. It means that if we take <m>x</m> large
enough we can make <m>g(x)</m> as close to <m>L_g</m> as we would like. In
particular, we would like for <m>\abs{g(x)-L_g}\lt\delta</m> as in the
sketch below.
</p>

<image source="images/LimComp1.png" width="70%" />
<!-- \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1.3in,width=3.5in]{../Figures/LimComp1}} -->
<p>

Therefore, we can find a number <m>B</m> such that for every <m>x\gt B</m>,
<m>\abs{g(x)-L_g}\lt\delta</m>.
If we take  <m>y=g(x)</m>, then we have <m>\abs{y-L_g}\lt\delta</m>.
</p>
<p>



From the continuity of <m>f</m> at <m>L_g</m> we know  that
<m>\abs{g(x)-L_g}=\abs{y-L_g}\lt\delta</m> means that
<me>
\abs{f(g(x))-f(L_g)}=\abs{f(y)-f(L_g)}\lt\eps.
</me>
</p>
<p>
<alert>END OF SCRAPWORK</alert>
</p>
</investigation>

<proof>
<p>
  Let <m>\eps\gt 0</m> be given.
  
  Since <m>f(y)</m> is continuous at <m>L_g</m> there is a real number
  <m>\delta\gt0</m> such that
<me>\text{if }\abs{y-L_g}\lt\delta\text{ then }\abs{f(y)-f(L_g)}\lt\eps.</me>

  Since <m>\tlimit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}=L_g</m> there is a real number <m>B</m> such
  that
  <me>
  \text{ if } x\gt B \text{ then } \abs{g(x)-L_g} \lt \delta.
  </me>
  Take <m>B</m> be the lower bound needed to guarantee that
  <m>\abs{g(x)-L_g}\lt\delta</m>. If <m>x\gt B</m> then since <m>y=g(x)</m>
  <me>
  \abs{y-L_g}=\abs{g(x)-L_g}\lt\delta,
  </me>
  and since  <m> \abs{y-L_g}\lt\delta</m> we see, from the continuity of <m>f</m>
  at <m>L_g</m> that <m>\abs{f(y)-f(L_g)}\lt\eps</m>.

  Therefore <m>
  \limit{x}{\infty}{f(g(x))} = f(L_g) =
  f\left(\tlimit{x}{\infty}{g(x)}\right).
  </m>

  


</p>
<p>
<alert><m>\halmos</m></alert>
</p>
</proof>





