</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="SUBSECTIONOneOverXIsCont">
<title>The Function    <m>f(x)=\frac1x</m> is Continuous
  Wherever  It Is Defined</title>

<lemma xml:id="LEMMA1overxIsCont">
<p>
    The function <m>f(x)=\frac1x</m> is continuous at <m>a\neq0</m>.
  </p>
</lemma>
<p>
  You will need <xref ref="LEMMA1overxIsCont">Lemma</xref> to solve
  <xref ref="PROBLEMProofOfQuotLim">Problem</xref> below.  We will provide the
  scrapwork and leave the formal proof as a problem for you.
</p>
<investigation>
 <p> To keep things simple (this is scrapwork, after all) we will first
  assume that <m>a\gt0</m>. If we have an <m>\eps\gt0</m> then by
  <xref ref="DEFINITIONcontinuity">Theorem</xref> we need to find a <m>\delta\gt0</m> such
  that if <m>\abs{x-a}\lt\delta</m> then <m>\abs{\frac1x-\frac1a}\lt\eps</m>. As
  usual we work backwards.
</p>
<p>

  Combining the fractions we see that
  <me>
  \abs{\frac1x-\frac1a}=\frac{\abs{a-x}}{a\abs{x}}=\frac{\abs{x-a}}{a\abs{x}},
  </me>
  so  we need to find a <m>\delta\gt0</m> such that <m>\abs{x-a}\lt\delta</m>
  ensures that <m>\frac{\abs{x-a}}{a\abs{x}}\lt\eps</m>.
</p>
<p>

  At first it appears that all we need to do choose
  <m>\delta \lt \eps\cdot a \cdot\abs{x}</m>. If we could do that we<rsq/>d have
  <m> \abs{x-a}\lt\delta = \eps\cdot a \cdot\abs{x}</m> in which case
  <me>
  \abs{\frac1x-\frac1a}=\frac{\abs{x-a}}{a\abs{x}}=\frac{\abs{x-a}}{a}\cdot\frac{1}{\abs{x}}\lt\eps.
  </me>
</p>
<p>

  But of course we<rsq/>ve seen this before. Just as in the proof of
  <xref ref="LEMMALimProd1">Lemma</xref>, <m>\delta</m> must be a constant; it cannot
  depend on <m>x</m>. So we need to replace <m>\frac1x</m> with a constant
  somehow.
  The Algebra here gets  a bit delicate. We strongly recommend that you
  visualize each step of the following argument with a  sketch like
  the one we used in the scrapwork for <xref ref="THEOREMLimCompInf">Theorem</xref>
</p>
<p>

  Suppose we choose <m>\delta\gt0</m> such that
<me>    \abs{x-a} \lt\frac{a}{2}.</me>
Then we see that
<me>    -\frac{a}{2}\lt x-a \lt\frac{a}{2}</me>
or

<mdn>
<mrow  xml:id="EQUATION1overXBndFromZero">
   \frac{a}{2}\amp{}=a -\frac{a}{2}\lt x
% \label{eq:1overXBndFromZero}
   </mrow>
   <mrow number="no">
    \amp \lt a+\frac{a}{2}=\frac{3a}{2}.
</mrow>
</mdn>

  Thus if we make <m>\abs{x-a}\lt\frac{a}{2}</m>, we see that
  <m>0\lt\frac{a}{2}\lt x</m> and so, not the right side.}
  <me>
  \frac{1}{\abs{x}}=\frac{1}{x}\lt\frac{2}{a}
  </me>
  for all <m>x\gt0</m>.
  </p>
  <aside>
<title>Comment</title>
<p>
Notice that we are using the left side of <xref
ref="EQUATION1overXBndFromZero"></xref>
</p>
</aside>

<p>

  Therefore
  <m>\abs{\frac1x-\frac1a}=\frac{\abs{x-a}}{a}\cdot\frac{1}{\abs{x}}\lt\frac{2}{a^2}\abs{x-a}</m>. Thus
  if we choose <m>\delta</m> to be  the lesser of <m>\frac{a}{2}</m> and
  <m>\frac{\eps a^2}{2}</m> we have everything we need to conclude that
  <m>\tlimit{x}{a}{\frac1x}=\frac1a</m> for <m>a\gt 0.</m>
</p>
<p>
<alert>END OF SCRAPWORK</alert>
</p>
</investigation>

